{{redirect-multi|2|Cacophony|Euphony}}
'''Phonaesthetics''' (from the {{lang-grc-gre|φωνή}} ''phōnē'', "voice-sound"; and {{lang-grc-gre|αἰσθητική}} ''aisthētikē'', "aesthetics") is the philosophical study of beauty ([[aesthetics]]) within the sounds of human speech ([[phonetics]]), or the scientific study of perceptions about beauty in such sounds. The term is not formally established in either philosophy or linguistics. According to Irish linguist Raymond Hickey, phonaesthetics is concerned with "the possible connection between sound sequences and meaning"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hickey |first1=Raymond |title=A Dictionary of Varieties of English |date=2013 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=111858404X |page=514 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kWpXAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT514 |language=en}}</ref> particularly through [[sound symbolism]], and according to British linguist [[David Crystal]], it is "a term sometimes used in linguistics to refer to the study of the aesthetic properties of sound".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crystal |first1=David |title=Dictionary of Linguistics and Phonetics |date=2011 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781444356755 |page=364 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=3ZPQVuSgDAkC&pg=PT364 |language=en}}</ref> According to Crystal:
{{quote|Examples include the implication of smallness in the [[close vowel]]s of such words as ''teeny weeny'', and the unpleasant associations of the consonant cluster ''sl-'' in such words as ''slime'', ''slug'', and ''slush''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Crystal|first1=David|title=A Dictionary of Language|date=2001 |publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226122038|page=260|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3GU5FWs1pBEC&pg=PA260|language=en}}</ref>}}The application of said aesthetic properties of sound, phonaesthetics, and their meaning in [[Media (communication)|media]] has yet to be studied extensively. That being said, the study of sound [[aesthetics]] is a burgeoning field waiting to be studied by phonaestheticians everywhere.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
Sound has many qualitative aspects, some of which are subjectively regarded as euphony and cacophony.
== Euphony == Euphony is the effect of sounds being pleasant, rhythmical, or harmonious.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://web.cn.edu/kwheeler/lit_terms_C.html|title=CACOPHONY, Literary Terms and Definition by Carson-Newman University|date=|accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://literarydevices.net/cacophony/|title=Definition of Cacophony|date=|accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref><ref name="ElizabethPodhaizer2001">{{cite book|last1=Elizabeth|first1=Mary|last2=Podhaizer|first2=Mary Elizabeth|title=Painless Poetry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PL-Lpq-BbucC&pg=RA1-PT186|year=2001|publisher=Barron's Educational Series|isbn=978-0-7641-1614-8|chapter=Euphony}}</ref> An example of euphony is the poem ''Some Sweet Day''.
{{quote|<poem> Some day Love shall claim his own Some day Right ascend his throne, Some day hidden Truth be known; Some day—some sweet day. </poem>|"Some Sweet Day", [[Lewis J. Bates]]}}{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
== Cacophony == Cacophony is the effect of sounds being harsh and often discordant. These sounds are often meaningless and jumbled together.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cacophony|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/cacophony?s=t|website=Dictionary.com|accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref> A discordant series of harsh, unpleasant sounds helps to convey disorder. This is often furthered by the combined effect of the meaning and the difficulty of pronunciation. For example:
{{quote|<poem>My stick fingers click with a snicker And, chuckling, they knuckle the keys; Light-footed, my steel feelers flicker And pluck from these keys melodies.</poem> |"Player Piano", [[John Updike]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Poetic Devices|url=http://www.chaparralpoets.org/devices.pdf|website=chaparralpoets.org|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>}}
